Waterfowl - LTEM - Mahoney Lake Ecological Reserve

Published

2023-02-23

1 Summary of Waterfowl LTEM protocol

1.1 Basic protocol

As taken from the protocol document:

âEstablish observation points at enough sites to provide views of the entire survey area. â¦

Choose a date after which migrants are mostly gone. Count on 3 separate occasions during a 2-3 week period and keep > highest count.â

The data collected under this protocol at each survey consists of the following variables:

  • Species. The species of waterfowl counted.
  • Sex. The sex of the species.
  • Count. The number of birds of this species and sex. Choose a date after which migrants are mostly gone

1.2 Cautions about the protocol.

1.2.1 Donât use 0 to indicate a missing value.

If no species were seen during a visit, this is indicated by the species code being set to missing and the count field being set to 0. This needs to be done consistently over time.

If no visit was made to a station in a year, then there are no records in the database.

1.2.2 Classifying by season

The protocol is silent about seasonal sampling, e.g., spring vs.Â fall. There is some issue on how to properly pool information that is close together but crosses year boundaries. For example, surveys may be done in late December of 2013 and early January of 2014. If the maximum counts over multiple visits in the winter are collected, visits on these two months need to be âcombinedâ even though they are in different calendar years.

For this analysis we classified by month (November, December, January, February) to avoid this problem

1.3 Database structure

The relevant fields from the database are:

  • SAMPLE_LABEL. The label for the location where data was located.
  • Date. The date the data was collected. The Year is extracted from this date.
  • Species. What species were seen
  • Count. Count of the number of birds of each species.

2.1 Variables names corrected for R

Variable names in R must start with a letter and contain letters or numbers or underscores. Blanks in variable names are not normally allowed, nor are special characters such as %. These are normally replaced by periods (â.â) in the variable name.

3 Single Site Analysis

Date for the Mahoney Lake Ecological Reserve are available from 2015 to 2020.

This design has multiple stations that are repeatedly measured over time with multiple measurements at each station Please refer to the Fitting Trends with Complex Study Designs document in the CommonFile directory for information on fitting trends with complex study designs.

All analyses were done using the R (R Core Team, 2022) analysis system. All plots are also saved as separate *png files for inclusion into other reports.

3.1 Maximum counts

The data is first summarized to the date level by summing the count over the different species for each date-sample station combination. This reduces the data to one measurement per date per site/year.

A preliminary plot of the total count is found in FigureÂ 1.

Notice that there may be evidence of station effect, where for example, the number of birds at certain stations are generally higher than at the other stations because of local station-specific conditions (e.g.Â better habitat).

Next the maximum count in each month in each station (but only November, December, January, and February) is found. The maximum counts are:
